{"title_page": "Long hair", "text_new": "{{about|human head hair|other uses|Longhair (disambiguation)}}\n[[File:Wenceslas Hollar - Young man with long hair (State 1).jpg|230px|right|thumb|A man with shoulder length hair, 1599]]\n[[File:KonkanaBakshi.jpg|250px|right|thumb|A woman with waist length hair]]\n'''Long hair''' is kak to work with. Long hair is a [[hairstyle]] where the [[head hair]] is allowed to grow to a considerable length. Exactly what constitutes long hair can change from culture to culture, or even within cultures. For example, a woman with chin-length hair in some cultures may be said to have short hair, while a man with the same length of hair in some of the same cultures would be said to have long hair.\n\nLong hair proves time and time again to be '''kak''' to work with. Men should stop being horny. Go outside and plant a tree\n\nMales having short, cut hair are in many cultures viewed as being under society's control, such as while in the military or prison or as punishment for a crime. Long lustrous female hair is generally rated [[Physical attractiveness|attractive]] by both men and women across cultures.<ref>{{cite book|first=David M. |last=Buss|title=The handbook of evolutionary psychology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=esDW3xTKoLIC&pg=PA309 |year=2005|publisher=John Wiley and Sons|isbn=978-0-471-26403-3|page=309}}</ref><ref name=\"Bereczkei\">{{cite journal|author=Bereczkei, T. |title=Hair length, facial attractiveness, personality attribution; A multiple fitness model of hairdressing|journal=Review of Psychology|volume=13|issue=1 |year=2007|pages=35\u201342|url=http://hrcak.srce.hr/9060?lang=en}}</ref> The prevalence of [[trichophilia]] (hair partialism or [[fetishism]]) is 7% in the population, and very long hair is a common subject of devotion in this group.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Scorolli | first1 = C | last2 = Ghirlanda | first2 = S | last3 = Enquist | first3 = M | last4 = Zattoni | first4 = S | last5 = Jannini | first5 = E A | title = Relative prevalence of different fetishes | journal = International Journal of Impotence Research | volume = 19 | issue = 4 | pages = 432\u20137 | year = 2007 | pmid = 17304204 | doi = 10.1038/sj.ijir.3901547 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hairstylenation.com/heels-top-global-fetish-leaderboard/ |location=England |title=Heels top the global fetish leader board |access-date=2014-07-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714113006/http://www.hairstylenation.com/heels-top-global-fetish-leaderboard/ |archive-date=2014-07-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Biological significance==\n[[File:\u80cc\u4e2d (10675203514) (cropped).jpg|right|thumb|A woman with mid-back level hair]]\nHumans, [[horse]]s, [[orangutan]]s and [[lion]]s are among the few species that may grow their head hair or [[wikt:mane|mane]]s very long. Humans are believed to have lost their fur 2.5\u20133 million years ago as [[hominid]]s when transitioning from a forest habitat to the open savanna, as an effect of [[natural selection]], since this development made it possible to run fast and hunt animals close to the equator without getting overheated. Head hair was an exception, which was a survival trait because it provides [[thermal insulation]] of the scalp from the sun, protects against [[Ultraviolet|ultraviolet radiation]] exposure(UV), and also provides cooling (when sweat evaporates from soaked hair).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.philpoteducation.com/mod/book/tool/print/index.php?id=783&chapterid=1038|title=2.2 Applications and skills|website=www.philpoteducation.com|access-date=2019-11-07}}</ref> The ability to grow [[straight hair]] has been observed among [[Homo sapiens]] sub-groups in less sunny regions further away from the equator. Relative to kinked [[Afro-textured hair]], straight hair allows more UV light to pass to the scalp (which is essential for the production of vitamin D, that is important for bone development<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/figure/The-role-of-ARA-in-bone-development-and-homeostatic-regulation-of-vitamin-D3-and_fig3_301247535|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>).\n\nScientists also view the ability to grow very long hair as a result of [[sexual selection]], since long and healthy hair is a sign of fertility and youth.<ref name = watson>{{cite book |last=Watson |first=James |title=Darwin: the Indelible Stamp; the Evolution of an Idea |location=Philadelphia |publisher=Running Press |year=2005 |page=[https://archive.org/details/indeliblestampev00darw/page/1042 1042] |isbn=0-7624-2136-3 |url=https://archive.org/details/indeliblestampev00darw/page/1042 }}</ref>{{quotation needed|date=December 2012}} An [[evolutionary biology]] explanation for this attraction is that hair length and quality can act as a cue to youth and health, signifying a woman's reproductive potential.<ref name=Hinsz/> As hair grows slowly, long hair may reveal 2\u20133 years of a person's health status, nutrition, age and reproductive fitness. Malnutrition, and deficiencies in minerals and vitamins due to starvation, cause loss of hair or changes in hair color (e.g. dark hair turning reddish).<ref name=EPHandbook2005>Sugiyama, Lawrence S. (2005) \"Physical Attractiveness in Adaptationist Perspective\", Chapter 10 in Buss, David M. (ed.) ''The Handbook of Evolutionary Psychology''. John Wiley & Sons, Inc. {{ISBN|978-0-471-26403-3}}</ref>\n\n==Psychological significance==\n[[Anthropologists]] speculate that the functional significance of long head hair may be [[adornment]], a by-product of secondary [[natural selection]] once other [[androgenic hair|androgenic]]/[[Somatic (biology)|somatic]] hair (body hair) had largely been lost. Another possibility is that long head hair is a result of [[Fisherian runaway]] [[sexual selection]], where long lustrous hair is a visible [[Genetic marker|marker]] for a healthy individual. For some groups or individuals, however, short hair is the selected trait.<ref name = watson/>\n\nBy seven to nine months, infants can tell the sexes apart based on hair length, voice pitch, and faces.<ref>{{cite book |first1=Simon Johnson |last1=Williams |first2=Lynda I. A. |last2=Birke |first3=Gillian |last3=Bendelow |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xrK15NBbYQcC&pg=PA130|title=Debating biology: sociological reflections on health, medicine, and society |page=130 |publisher=Routledge |year=2003 |isbn=0-415-27903-8}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural meaning==\nWays of life often viewed as more rigid, such as soldiering and religious discipline, frequently have explicit rules regarding hair length. For example, Buddhist monks shave their heads as part of their order of worship.<ref name = leach>{{cite journal|last=Leach |first=E. R. |authorlink=Edmund Leach |title=Magical Hair |journal=Journal of the Royal Anthropological Institute |date=July 1958 |volume=88 |issue=2 |pages=147\u2013164 |doi=10.2307/2844249|jstor=2844249 }}</ref> Similarly, religious men with long hair include the [[Nazarites]] of the [[Hebrew Bible]] ([[Samson]] being a famous example)<ref name = judge/> and the [[Sikh]]s.<ref name = fowler/> Subservient cultures may view male long hair negatively, and are sometimes detected by their rulers through hair length, as was the case with the [[Gaelic Ireland|Gaelic Irish]] under English rule and the [[Reconquista|Moors under Spanish rule]] in [[Medieval]] [[Spain]].{{clarify|date=July 2014}}\n\nEast Asian cultures have traditionally associated unkempt hair in a woman with irresponsible attitude, as women in East Asia were expected to tie up their hair in styles such as the ponytail, plait, or any bun, as a symbol of responsibility.<ref name = asia/>\n\n==Transferred meaning==\nThe traditional connotation of \"long hair\" in [[English language|English]] meant, roughly, someone artistically knowledgeable or wise, an [[aesthete]].<ref name = OED>[[Oxford English Dictionary]]</ref> As a descriptive term, it has been applied to [[Merovingian dynasty|Merovingians]] and [[classical music]] enthusiasts, as well as [[hippie]]s and aesthetes.<ref name = OED/>\n\n==Hair lengths==\n<gallery widths=\"150\" heights=\"200\">\nFile:Girl with long black hair, rear view (1 November 2018).jpg|An Indonesian woman with shoulder length hair\nFile:Tracy E Caldwell portrait.jpg|The American astronaut [[Tracy Caldwell Dyson|Tracy Caldwell]] with armpit length hair\nFile:Apocalyptica Drive With Full Force 2018 20.jpg|Finnish cello player [[Perttu Kivilaakso]] with mid back length hair\nFile:\u80cc\u4e2d (2828530544).jpg|A Japanese woman with waist length hair\nFile:\" 12 - ITALY - FIAT - Girls at Bologna Motorshow 2012 01.jpg|An Italian woman with hip/tailbone length hair\nFile:Very long hair woman and her friend Sri Lanka.jpg|A Sri Lankan woman with classic length hair\nFile:Yungchen Lhamo.jpeg|A Tibetan woman with knee length hair\n</gallery>\n\nHair length is most often measured (in centimeters or inches) from the line of the [[scalp]] on the [[forehead]] up over the highest point of the skull to its termination, and sometimes from the crown, the latter resulting in 10 centimeter lower values in average.<ref name=\"Scalp-hair-length-II\"/> In [[cosmetology]], hair lengths are usually categorized according to the part of the body where the bulk of the longest hair terminates: ''chin level'', ''shoulder length'', ''lower shoulderblade''/''mid-back level'', ''waist length'', ''hip-length'', ''classic length'' (extends to almost ''buttock-length'', i.e. upper thigh-length, where the [[Human leg|legs]] meet the [[buttocks]]), ''thigh-length'', ''knee-length'' and ''ankle/floor length'' hair.<ref name=\"Scalp-hair-length-II\"/><ref name=cosmetology>{{cite book |first=Anthony |last=Gonzalez |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dKVBDlaGoAAC&pg=PT54 |title=Cosmetology |page=54 |publisher=Global Media |year=2007 |isbn=81-89940-45-7}}</ref>\n\nHair usually takes about two years to reach shoulder length,<ref name=Andropathy/> and about seven years to reach waist-length/hip-length, including occasional trims (approximately 80\u201390&nbsp;cm (32\u201336&nbsp;inches) from forehead for most people)<ref name=cosmetology/><ref name=Andropathy>{{cite book |first=R. A. S. |last=Hemat |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r1jCtGD4CcsC&pg=PA375 |title=Andropathy |page=375 |publisher=Urotext |year=2007 |isbn=1-903737-08-7}}</ref>\n\n===Maximum hair length===\n[[File:Pierre Auguste Renoir - Portrait de Julie Manet.jpg|210px|right|thumb|Portrait of Julie Manet by [[Pierre-Auguste Renoir|Renoir]], 1894]]\nThe maximum hair length that is possible to reach is about 15&nbsp;cm (6&nbsp;in) for infants (below the age of 1), about 60&nbsp;cm (24&nbsp;in) for children, and generally 100&nbsp;cm (40&nbsp;in) for adults. Documentation for decrease of the maximum length with age cannot be found in the literature. Some individuals can reach excessive lengths. Lengths greater than 150&nbsp;cm (59&nbsp;in) are frequently observed in long hair contests.<ref name=Robbins>{{cite book |first=Clarence R. |last=Robbins |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-UTEKeEypjEC&pg=PA11|title=Chemical and physical behavior of human hair |publisher=Springer |year=2002 |isbn=0-387-95094-X}}</ref> [[Xie Qiuping]] had the longest documented hair in the world, measuring 5.627 m (18&nbsp;ft 5.54 in) in May 2004.<ref>[http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/dedication/longest-hair-(female) Guinness World Records: Longest hair]. guinnessworldrecords.com</ref>\n\nThe maximum [[terminal hair]] length depends on the length of the [[Anagen phase|anagen]] (period of hair growth) for the individual. Waist-length hair or longer is only possible to reach for people with long anagen. The anagen lasts between 2 and 7 years, for some individuals even longer, and is followed by shorter [[catagen]] (transition) and [[telogen]] (resting) periods. At any given time, about 85% of hair strands are in anagen.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Principles of Anatomy & Physiology |edition=13 |author=Tortora & Derrickson |publisher=John Wiley & Sons, Inc |date=2012 |page=163}}</ref> The [[fibroblast growth factor 5]] (FGF5) gene affects the hair cycle in mammals including humans; blocking FGF5 in the human scalp (by applying a herbal extract that blocked FGF5) extends the hair cycle, resulting in less hair fall and increased hair growth.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.2336/nishinihonhifu.69.81| title = Sanguisorba Officinalis Root Extract Has FGF-5 Inhibitory Activity and Reduces Hair Loss by Causing Prolongation of the Anagen Period| journal = Nishi Nihon Hifuka| volume = 69| pages = 81| year = 2007| last1 = Maeda | first1 = T. | last2 = Yamamoto | first2 = T. | last3 = Isikawa | first3 = Y. | last4 = Itoh | first4 = N. | last5 = Arase | first5 = S. }}</ref>\n\n==Cultural history==\n'''South Africa'''\n\nIt depends if you are a boer or an English ou. Mainly the English have their hair short and the Afrikaans grow theirs long. \n<br />\n===Europe===\n\n====Ancient Greece and Rome====\n[[File:Bust of Zeus.jpg|thumb|[[Ancient Rome|Roman]] marble colossal head of a long-haired [[Zeus]], 2nd century AD.]]\nIn [[ancient Greece]], long male hair was a symbol of wealth and power, while a shaven head was appropriate for a slave. The ancient Greeks had several gods and heroes who wore their hair long, including [[Zeus]], [[Achilles]], [[Apollo]], and [[Poseidon]]. Greek soldiers are said to have worn their hair long in battle. Such warriors considered it a sign of aristocracy and are said to have combed it openly in order to show off.  Also, in order to keep enemies from getting a hold of it in battle, they were known to cut the front short, but leave it long in the back, where it was more out of reach ([[Mullet (haircut)|mullet]]). A widely held alternative interpretation of the conventional belief is that they kept it long, and simply tied it back in a style known as a [[ponytail]] in order to keep it out of their enemies' reach. The ponytail method allowed warriors, who often traveled to battle with a minimal amount of equipment in order to avoid excessively heavy loads over long marches, to keep their hair manageable with a small piece of string to hold their pony tail in place and a knife to cut the back to length with one simple slice. Around the sixth century, however, the Greek men shifted to shorter hairstyles, with the exception of the Spartans. Women in the culture remained with the longer style, which for them showed freedom, health, and wealth, as well as good behavior.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Irwin |first=M. Eleanor |title=Odysseus' \"Hyacinthine Hair\" in 'Odyssey' 6.231 |journal=Phoenix |date=Oct 1990 |volume=44 |issue=3 |pages=205\u2013218 |doi=10.2307/1088933|jstor=1088933 }}</ref> In men, long hair was considered a sign of false pride by this time.<ref name = barbers>{{cite journal |last=Nicolson |first=Frank W. |title=Greek and Roman Barbers |journal=Harvard Studies in Classical Philology |year=1891 |volume=2 |pages=41\u201356|url=https://archive.org/details/jstor-310326|jstor=310326}}</ref>\n\n[[Pliny the Elder]] in his ''[[Natural History (Pliny)|Natural History]]'' and [[Varro]] related that the Romans did not begin to cut their hair short until barbers were introduced to Italy from Sicily by P. Ticinius Mena in 299 BC.<ref>[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.02.0137%3Abook%3D7%3Achapter%3D59 Pliny the Elder at Perseus]</ref> Women in Roman times valued long hair, usually with a center part. Apart from in the earliest times, men's hair was usually shorter than women's, although other cultures of the time, such as Greeks in the east, considered long hair to be typical of philosophers, who were thought to be too engrossed in learning to bother with hair.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Bartman |first=Elizabeth |title=Hair and the Artifice of Roman Female Adornment |journal=American Journal of Archaeology |date=Jan 2001 |volume=105 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201325 |jstor=507324}}</ref> Strictly in the province of Rome, however, the shorter hairstyle was especially popular.<ref name = barbers/> When Julius Caesar conquered the [[Gauls]], who favored long hair, he ordered it to be cut short.<ref>{{cite book |last=Felt |first=Joseph |title=Customs of New England |location=New York |publisher=Burt Franklin |year=1967 |page=187 |isbn=0-8337-1105-9}}</ref>\n\n====Middle Ages====\nIn the European [[middle ages]], shorter hair often signified servitude and peasantry, while long hair was often attributed to freemen, as was the case with the Germanic [[Goths]] and [[Merovingians]].\n\nThe [[Gaelic Ireland|Gaelic Irish]] (both men and women)<ref name=\"Connolly-prologue\">{{cite book |title=Contested island: Ireland 1460\u20131630 |last=Connolly |first=Sean J |year=2007 |publisher=Oxford University Press |page=7 |chapter=Prologue}}</ref> took great pride in their long hair\u2014for example, a person could be heavily fined for cutting a man's hair short against his will.<ref name=\"Ginnell7\">[http://www.libraryireland.com/Brehon-Laws/Contents.php ''The Brehon Laws: A Legal Handbook: Chapter VII''], Laurence Ginnell (1894)</ref> When the Anglo-Normans and the English colonized Ireland, hair length came to signify one's allegiance. Irishmen who cut their hair short were deemed to be forsaking their Irish heritage. Likewise, English colonists who wore their hair long in the back were deemed to be forsaking their role as English subjects and giving in to the Irish life. Thus, hair length was one of the most common ways of judging a true Englishman in this period.  Muslims in Christian areas were ordered to keep their hair short and parted, as their longer style was considered rebellious and barbaric.<ref name = ma>{{cite journal|last=Bartlett |first=Robert |title=Symbolic Meanings of Hair in the Middle Ages |journal=Transactions of the Royal Historical Society |year=1994 |series=Sixth series |volume=4 |pages=43\u201360|doi=10.2307/3679214|jstor=3679214 }}</ref>\n[[File:Empress Elisabeth of Austria.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Empress Elisabeth of Austria]] wearing thigh-length hair in 1865. (Painting by [[Franz Xaver Winterhalter]])]]\n\nThe long hair tradition was widespread among English and French men in the 11th and 12th centuries, though it was considered, mostly because of endorsement of the [[Roman Catholic Church]], acceptable for men also to have shorter hair.  The tradition was largely brought about by monarchs who rejected the shorter hairstyle, causing the people to follow. [[Wulfstan (died 1023)|Wulfstan]], a religious leader, worried that those with longer hair would fight like women, and be unable to protect England from foreign invasion. This idea can be found in later military leaders as well, such as those of the [[Confederate States of America|American Confederacy]].<ref>{{cite book|last=McManus|first=Howard Rollins|title=The Battle of Cloids Mountain of Virginia, 1864|publisher=University of Michigan|year=1989|isbn=|page=35}}<!--ISBN 0-930919-89-0?--></ref> Knights and rulers would also sometimes cut or pull out their hair in order to show penitence and mourning, and a squire's hair was generally shorter than a knight's. Married women who let their hair flow out in public were frowned upon, as this was normally reserved for the unwed, although they were allowed to let it out in mourning, to show their distressed state. Through these centuries it was expected of [[Eastern Christian]]s to wear long hair as well as long beards, which was especially expected from clergy and monks.\n\nIn England, during the [[English Civil War]]s of 1642 to 1651, male hair length was emblematic of the disputes between [[Cavaliers]] and [[Roundheads]] (Puritans).  Cavaliers wore longer hair, and were less religious-minded, thought of by the Roundheads as lecherous.  The more devout Roundheads typically had somewhat shorter hair.<ref name = leach/>\n\nAround this time, long hair in England also came to be associated with adventurers who traveled to America and were familiar with the native culture there, short hair with less adventurous types.\n\n====Trends among women in 20th and 21st centuries====\n<gallery widths=\"150\" heights=\"200\">\nFile:The Seven Sutherland Sisters.jpg|The Seven Sutherland Sisters were singing and showing off their famous floor-length hair in a sideshow of Barnum & Bailey's from about 1882 to 1907.\nFile:Mary_Garden_in_Debussy%27s_Pell%C3%A9as_et_M%C3%A9lisande_2.jpg|Opera singer [[Mary Garden]] in 1908 with knee-length hair\nFile:Dewi-persik.jpg|[[Dewi Persik]] with waist-length hair\nFile:Woman with very long hair.JPG|[[Dutch people|Dutch]] woman with thigh-length hair\nFile:TweiMadchen vonSangaflussCentralafrika.jpg|[[Ngbandi people|Ngbandi]] girls with hip-length hair\n</gallery>\n\nGrowing and wearing long hair was common among women in the Western world until World War One.<ref name = cosmetology/> Long female hair never ceased in western culture, though it was rare during the 1920s and 1930s.\n\nIn most current cultures, it is more typical for women to wear long hair than for men to do so. An American study shows significant correlation between hair length and age, which indicates that younger women tend to have longer hair than older women. A significant correlation was also found between women's hair length and hair quality. Moreover, hair quality was correlated with the women's perceived physical health. Consistent with principles of [[evolutionary psychology]], these results indicate that hair length and quality can act as a cue to a woman's youth and health, signifying reproductive potential. The correlation between the woman's hair length and marital status, or number of children, was however not more than to be expected from the correlation between hair length and age.<ref name=Hinsz>{{cite journal |first1=Verlin B. |last1=Hinsz |first2=David C. |last2=Matz |first3=Rebecca A. |last3=Patience |title=Does women's hair signal reproductive potential? |journal=Journal of Experimental Social Psychology|year=2001 |volume=37 |issue=2 |page=166 |doi=10.1006/jesp.2000.1450}}</ref>\n\n====Trends among men in 20th and 21st centuries====\n[[File:Aankomst Beatles op Schiphol, de Beatles tijdens persconferentie John Lennon, Bestanddeelnr 916-5131.jpg|thumb|Long male hair in western youth culture became popular in the 1960s and 70s with [[The Beatles]].]]\n[[File:Bob-Marley-in-Concert Zurich 05-30-80.jpg|thumb|[[Bob Marley]] made [[rastafari]] culture and [[dreadlocks]] popular also outside [[Jamaica]].]]\n[[File:Black Sabbath, original lineup (1973).JPG|thumb|[[Black Sabbath]]. A long hair is very popular in [[Heavy metal subculture]].]]\nBefore World War One men generally had longer hair and beards. However, short hair on men was introduced in World War One for soldiers. Slaves and defeated armies were often required to shave their heads. The [[trench warfare]] in 1914 to 1918 exposed men to [[flea]] and [[lice infestations]], which prompted the order to cut hair short, establishing a military tradition.<ref name = cosmetology/>\n\nBeat poets during the 1950s wore longer hairstyles. By 1960, a small \"[[beatnik]]\" community in [[Newquay]], Cornwall, England (including a young [[Wizz Jones]]) had attracted the attention of their neighbors for growing their hair to a length past the shoulders, resulting in a television interview with [[Alan Whicker]] on BBC television's ''[[Tonight (1957 TV series)|Tonight]]'' series.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W3WfXA9JL9w Whicker, Alan. ''Tonight'': \"Beatniks in Newquay\". BBC, 1960.]</ref> The 1960s also introduced [[The Beatles]], who started a more widespread longer hair trend. The [[social revolution]] of the 1960s led to a renaissance of unchecked hair growth,<ref name = cosmetology/> and long hair, especially on men, was worn as a political or [[Counterculture of the 1960s|countercultural]] symbol or protest and as a symbol of masculinity. This cultural symbol extended to several Western countries in the Americas, Western Europe, South Africa, and Australia.<ref name = gay>{{Citation |last=Bronski |first=Michael |title=The Pleasure Principle: Sex, Backlash, and the Struggle for Gay Freedom |publisher=Stonewall Inn Editions |year=2000 |pages=95\u201396 |isbn=0-312-25287-0}}</ref> Specific long hairstyles such as [[dreadlocks]] have been part of counterculture movements seeking to define other alternative cultures and lifestyles since this time.<ref name=\"asia\"/> Longer hair in general remained popular due to the youth rebellion throughout the liberal decade of the 1960s.<ref name = gay/> The long hair trend grew with the spread of the [[hippie]] movement in the 1960s<ref name = gay/> and, in the 1970s, longer hair styles would become the norm among men and women.\n\nIn the 1970s, the popularity of [[Jamaica]]'s [[reggae]] music and musician [[Bob Marley]] prompted interest in [[dreadlocks]] internationally. The anti-establishment philosophy of [[Rastafari movement|Rastafari]], echoed in much of the reggae of the time, resonated with left-leaning youth of all ethnicities \u2013 especially and primarily among [[African American]]s and other [[Black people|Blacks]], but among [[counterculture]] [[Whites]] as well.<ref>{{Citation |last1=Gossai |first1=Hemchand |first2=Nathaniel |last2=Murrell |title=Religion, Culture, and Tradition in the Caribbean |location=New York |publisher=St. Martin's Press |year=2000 |pages=181\u2013190 |isbn=0-312-23242-X}}</ref> [[Eastern Christian]]s are encouraged {{By whom|date=June 2017}} to wear long hair with long beard. In the 1980s the view of long hair as a solitary signifier of political or counter-cultural identity was countered and parodied in films such as [[Rambo (film series)|Rambo]] and many other militaristic heroes of media which challenged then-contemporary views of tradition.<ref>{{Citation |last=Lu |first=Hsiao-Peng |title=Transnational Chinese Cinemas |location=Honolulu |publisher=University of Hawaii Press |year=1997 |page=[https://archive.org/details/transnationalchi0000unse/page/229 229] |isbn=0-8248-1845-8 |url=https://archive.org/details/transnationalchi0000unse/page/229 }}</ref> In the 2000s longer hairstyles among men became popular among neopagans and [[rock music|rock]] enthusiasts;<ref>{{Citation |last=Weinstein |first=Deena |title=Heavy Metal |location=New York |publisher=Da Capo Press |year=2000 |page=129 |isbn=0-306-80970-2}}</ref> for example, musicians in [[heavy metal music|metal]] bands and their fans often wear long hair. Long hair may be grown for the purpose of being [[donate]]d to an [[organization]], such as [[Locks of Love]], for [[hairpiece]]s to help those who could not have hair otherwise, such as those who are diagnosed with [[alopecia areata]]. Today long hair has gained even more popularity. Even among mainstream men it is socially acceptable to have hair reaching around the upper back. This could in part be due to the \"man bun\" trend where men pull their shoulder length or longer hair back into a topknot [[Bun (hairstyle)|bun]].\n\n===Americas===\n====Native Americans====\n[[File:Yakima boy.png|thumb|right|[[Yakama people|Yakima]] boy with ''mid-back level'' hair. (Photo by [[Edward S. Curtis]], 1868\u20131952.)]]\nMany [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] men wore long hair before the arrival of western influences on their culture. (In Cherokee legends, for example, males said to be handsome were often described as having \"long hair almost to the ground\" or similar formulas.<ref>{{cite web |last=Kirk |first=Lowell |title=Cherokee Myths and Legends |year=1999 |url=http://www.telliquah.com/cherokee.htm |accessdate =2007-09-09 }}</ref>). Both men and women of these cultures have frequently struggled to maintain their tradition but have faced heavy opposition. Many consider it a sign of giving in to western influences to have their hair cut.<ref>{{Citation |last=Ferris |first=Jeri |title=Native American Doctor |location=Minneapolis |publisher=Carolrhoda Books |year=1991 |pages=32\u201333 |isbn=0-87614-443-1}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |last=Kilcup |first=Karen |title=Native American Women's Writing, C. 1800\u20131924 |location=Cambridge |publisher=Blackwell Publishers |year=2000 |pages=314\u2013316 |isbn=0-631-20518-7}}</ref> Early American settlers saw long-haired, native men as rebelling against their civilized society. Mountain men and trappers who adopted the customs were also considered amoral, and often identified by their long hair.<ref>{{Citation |last=Cavallo |first=Dominick |title=A Fiction of the past |location=New York |publisher=St. Martin's Press |year=1999 |page=[https://archive.org/details/fictionofpastsix00cava/page/90 90] |isbn=0-312-23501-1 |url=https://archive.org/details/fictionofpastsix00cava/page/90 }}</ref> Since the cultural movements of the Sixties and Seventies, however, Native Americans have felt less pressure to have short hair, as different movements have defended their cultural rights.<ref>{{Citation |last=Nagel |first=Joane |title=American Indian Ethnic Renewal |location=Oxford Oxfordshire |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=1997 |page=[https://archive.org/details/americanindianet0000nage/page/191 191] |isbn=0-19-512063-9 |url=https://archive.org/details/americanindianet0000nage/page/191 }}</ref> For example, several states have loosened prison regulations, allowing Native Americans to wear long hair during incarceration, along with other cultural allowances.<ref>{{Citation |last=French |first=Laurence |title=Native American Justice |location=Lanham |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers, Inc |year=2003 |pages=113\u2013117 |isbn=0-8304-1575-0}}</ref> There has been resistance to these changes, however, as long hair is sometimes used to hide drugs, as well as to identify with a gang.<ref>{{Citation |last=Fontana |first=Vincent |title=Municipal Liability |publisher=Aspen Law & Business Publishers |year=2003 |pages=241\u2013242 |isbn=0-7355-1375-9}}</ref>\n\n====African Americans====\nWhen African slaves were freed in America, they struggled to reach the social status of whites. Many former slaves tried to conform their hairstyles as part of this struggle. Women, especially, felt pressure to make their hair straight, rather than keeping the tightly coiled style they had known.<ref>[[#Byrd|Byrd]], pp. 25\u201349</ref> However, during the [[civil rights movement]] of the 1950s and 1960s, African-Americans such as [[Malcolm X]] advocated hairstyles such as [[afro]]s and [[dreadlocks]], in order to embrace their race, and to return to West African roots.<ref name=\"shame\">{{cite journal|last=Synnott|first=Anthony|date=September 1987|title=Shame and Glory: A Sociology of Hair|journal=The British Journal of Sociology|volume=38|issue=3|pages=381\u2013413|doi=10.2307/590695|jstor=590695}}</ref>\n\nSocial pressures at the time were heavily influencing these Americans (women) to have, straight hair, like white people did.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Taylor, Paul C. |title=Malcolm's Conk and Danto's Colors; Or, Four Logical Petitions concerning Race, Beauty, and Aesthetics|journal=The Journal of Aesthetics and Art Criticism|year=1999|volume= 57|issue=1 |pages=16\u201320|jstor=432060|doi=10.2307/432060}}</ref> This resulted in the [[Black is beautiful]] movement, wherein African Americans wore their long natural hair, that was however, untreated and unmodified. More recently, [[hair-extensions]] have become widespread. Scholars have pointed out the continued pressure on black women to have straight smooth hair. Amelia Jones points out that dolls for children, such as [[Barbie]]s, add to this pressure, citing as an example a new, black Barbie with straight hair. Blacks, she believes, should be able to be themselves without feeling pressured to \"tame\" their hair.<ref>Jones, Amelia (2003). ''The Feminism and Visual Culture Reader''. New York: Routledge. p. 343. {{ISBN|0415267056}}</ref>\n\n====Contemporary North America====\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float: right; margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 2em; font-size: 85%; background:#c6dbf7; color:black; width:30em; max-width: 25%;\" cellspacing=\"5\"\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n\"She, as a veil down to the slender waist,<br/>\nHer unadorned golden tresses wore<br/>\nDishevelled, but in wanton ringlets waved,<br/>\nAs the vine curls her tendrils...\"\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | \u2013 [[John Milton]]'s description of [[Eve]] in ''[[Paradise Lost]]''\n|}\n\nIn 1972, it was estimated that 24% of American women wore shoulder length hair or longer (44% of women in ages 14 to 44), meaning slightly more than 12% of men and women altogether. Similar frequency was found in 2001, when it was estimated that about 13% of the US adult population, male as well as females, has hair shoulder-length or longer, about 2.4% have hair reaching to the bottom of the shoulder blades or longer, about 0.3% have hair waist length or longer, and only about 0.017% have hair buttocks-length or longer.<ref name=\"Scalp-hair-length-I\">{{Cite journal\n | pmid = 12644859|url=http://journal.scconline.org/abstracts/cc2003/cc054n01/p00053-p00062.html\n| year = 2003\n| author1 = Robbins\n| first1 = C\n| title = Scalp hair length. I. Hair length in Florida theme parks: An approximation of hair length in the United States of America\n| journal = Journal of cosmetic science\n| volume = 54\n| issue = 1\n| pages = 53\u201362\n| last2 = Robbins\n| first2 = M. G.\n}}</ref> By [[extrapolating]] the above data and the number of hair length records, the number of people with shoulder-length hair or longer in the USA is estimated to be 27 million,  those with waist-length hair roughly 900,000, those with buttocks-length hair to be 40,000, with knee length hair to 2,000 and with ankle length hair to 70.<ref name=\"Scalp-hair-length-II\">Clarence Robbins and Marjorie Gene Robbins, [http://journal.scconline.org/pdf/cc2003/cc054n04/p00367-p00378.pdf \"Scalp hair length. II. Estimating the percentages of adults in the USA and larger populations by hari length.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217140616/http://journal.scconline.org/pdf/cc2003/cc054n04/p00367-p00378.pdf |date=2014-12-17 }} Journal of cosmetic science 54.4 (2003): 367\u2013378.</ref>\n\n===Africa===\n[[File:Halimaahmed2.jpg|thumb|right|[[Somali people|Somali]] woman with shoulder-length hair.]]\nThroughout much of Africa, [[afro-textured hair]] is the most frequent hair form, except among the [[Afro-Asiatic languages|Afro-Asiatic]] (Hamito-Semitic) speaking populations in [[North Africa]] and the [[Horn of Africa]]. In the latter regions, naturally long hair is instead more common.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hiernaux|first1=Jean|title=The People of Africa|date=1975|publisher=Scribners|isbn=0684140403|page=59|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=WJ-wAAAAIAAJ}}</ref>\n\nIn [[West Africa]]n cultures, women with long hair were highly valued. Long, thick hair was seen as a sign of health, strength, and capability to bear many children. In keeping with this general theme, women who were too young for marriage would shave a portion of their heads to signal so. This tradition, however, did not extend to every West African culture, as several valued shorter hair.<ref>[[#Byrd|Byrd]], pp. 2\u20135</ref>\n\n===Asia===\nHistorically, East Asian cultures viewed long hair as a sign of youth and aesthetic beauty. Long hair is associated with private life and sexuality. East Asian cultures see long, unkempt hair in a woman as a sign of sexual intent or a recent sexual encounter, as usually their hair is tied up.<ref name = asia>{{Citation |last=Maynard |first=Margaret |title=Dress and Globalisation |location=Manchester |publisher=Manchester University Press |year=2004 |page=104 |isbn=0-7190-6389-2}}</ref> Lay Buddhists have long hair, while Buddhist monks have shaved heads.<ref name = leach/>\n<gallery widths=\"150\" heights=\"200\">\nFile:Goyo Kamisuki.jpg|Japanese woman combing her long hair. (Colour woodblock print from 1920 by [[Hashiguchi Goy\u014d]].)\nFile:Ch5 wakamurasaki2.jpg|Illustration of [[The Tale of Genji]], painted by [[Tosa Mitsuoki]] (1617\u20131691).\nFile:Albazin Youth. Albazin Prisoners of War Professed the Orthodox Religion but Adopted Chinese Language and Customs after Capture by Manchurians in 1685. Beijing, 1874 WDL1941.png|Chinese orthodox Christian man from 1874\nFile:Nosu girls.jpg|[[Nosu]] girls in China 1922.\nFile:A hindoo fakeer with long hair.jpg|A hindoo \"[[fakir]]\" or Sadhu with long hair. Lithograph 1844 by [[Emily Eden]] after [[Lowes Cato Dickinson]].\n</gallery>\n\n====China====\nIn ancient China and Korea, hair was regarded as a precious legacy from parents. Most people would never cut their hair after they became adults, and cutting off one's hair was a penalty for minor crimes. Both men and women would coil up their hair and many hair-coiling styles were developed.\n\nBeginning in 1619, the ethnic [[Manchu]] [[Qing dynasty]] forced all men in China to adopt the [[Queue (hairstyle)|queue]]: a long braid down the back with the hair near the forehead completely shaved. Hair length and style became a life-or-death matter in 1645 as the Manchu told them either their hair or their head would be cut.\nNearly every [[Han Chinese|Han]] rebel group began by shearing this pigtail (most especially in the case of the [[Taiping Rebellion|Taiping]], who were known in Chinese as the \"Longhairs\"), but the queue on penalty of death lasted until 1911, when the Chinese people cut their queues in unison at a time of rebellion. Americans at first judged Chinese immigrant laborers to be poor workers because their long hair brought an association with women.<ref>{{Citation |last=Prasso |first=Sheridan |title=The Asian Mystique |location=New York |publisher=Public Affairs Press |year=2005 |pages=115\u2013116 |isbn=1-58648-214-9}}</ref>\n\nIslamic and Christian missionaries among the Chinese were strong advocates of shorter male hair for their converts.<ref name=\"reid\">{{cite book |last=Reid |first=Anthony |title=Southeast Asia in the Age of Commerce, 1450\u20131680 |location=New Haven |publisher=Yale University Press |year=1988 |page=82 |isbn=0-300-04750-9}}</ref> Around the Destruction of [[Four Olds]] period in 1964, almost anything seen as part of [[Culture of China|Traditional Chinese culture]] would lead to problems with the [[Communist Party of China|Communist]] [[Red Guards (China)|Red Guards]].  Items that attracted dangerous attention if caught in the public included [[jewelry]] and long male hair.<ref name=\"Law\">{{Citation |last=Law |first=Kam-yee |year=2003 |title=The Chinese Cultural Revolution Reconsidered: beyond purge and Holocaust |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |isbn=0-333-73835-7}}</ref> These things were regarded as symbols of [[bourgeois]] lifestyle, that represented wealth.  People had to avoid them or suffer serious consequences such as tortures and beatings by the guards.<ref name=\"Law\" /> More recently, long hair was ridiculed in China from October 1983 to December 1983, as part of the short and unsuccessful [[Anti-Spiritual Pollution Campaign]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Olympic crackdown on China's bad habits |publisher=BBC News |date=August 6, 2007 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/6927361.stm |accessdate = 2007-09-09 }}</ref>\n\nAlso, in Chinese ancient and modern poetry, long hair is a common [[symbol]] used by poets, for example [[Li Bai]] and [[Li Shangyin]], to express their depression and sadness.\n\n====Southeast Asia====\nIn [[Southeast Asia]] and [[Indonesia]], male long hair was valued until the seventeenth century, when the area adopted outside influences including Islam and Christianity. Invading cultures enforced shorter hairstyles on men as a sign of servitude, as well. They were also confused at the short hairstyles among women in certain areas, such as [[Thailand]], and struggled to explain why women in the area had such short hair. They came up with several mythical stories, one of which involved a king who found a long hair in his rice and, in a rage, demanded that all women keep their hair short.<ref name=\"reid\"/>\n\nIn rural areas in certain Asian countries, for example India, girls still usually let their hair grow long, and knee-length hair is not unusual.<ref name=Sherrow>Sherrow, Victoria (2006) [https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofha0000sher/page/242 ''Encyclopedia of hair: a cultural history''], Greenwood Publishing Group. p. 242. {{ISBN|0313331456}}</ref>\n\n====Japan====\n[[File:TANASHI CIMG5169.jpg|thumb|Japanese woman with long hair]]\nIn the medieval Japan, [[Heian period|heian]] men were not very interested in a woman's physical beauty and rarely had an opportunity to see it. The only physical attribute of interest was a woman's hair, which had to be thick and longer than she was tall. The fascination with long hair was one reason why a woman's becoming a nun was regarded with such seriousness&nbsp;\u2014 it could never again grow to its full length. This explains why [[Hikaru Genji|Genji]] refuses to let [[Murasaki]] (his de facto wife in the classical Japanese novel ''[[The Tale of Genji]]'') take the tonsure when she is ill.<ref>[[The Tale of Genji]], a novel about courtly life in medieval Japan.</ref>\n\n==In religion==\n\n===Judaism===\n[[File:Flickr_-_Government_Press_Office_(GPO)_-_A_Yemenite_Habani_family_celebrating_Passover.jpg|thumb|[[Habbani Jews]] feasting in a [[Passover]] [[Seder]]. Habbani Jews tend to lengthen their hair.]]\nIn the [[Old Testament]], the [[Nazirites]] would go for long periods of time without cutting their hair to show devotion to God.<ref>{{Bibleverse||Numbers|6:5}}, {{Bibleverse||Numbers|6:18\u201319}}</ref> [[Samson]] is one example; his strength depended upon his refraining from cutting his hair, described as worn in \"seven locks\".<ref name = judge>{{Bibleverse||Judges|13\u201316}}</ref>\n\nStrict Orthodox [[Judaism]] forbids men from cutting their [[Payot|sidelocks]], but other hair may be kept as desired. Hair is not cut during a time of mourning. The Torah in Deuteronomy 14:1 prohibits removing hair in mourning for the dead.\n\n===Christianity===\nIn the [[New Testament]], [[Saint Paul]] (formerly Saul of Tarsus) wrote, \"Doth not even nature itself teach you, that, if a man have long hair, it is a shame unto him? But if a woman have long hair, it is a glory to her: for her hair is given her for a covering. But if any seem contentious, we have no such custom, neither do the churches of God.\"<ref name = kjv>KJV {{Bibleverse|1|Corinthians|11:14\u201316|KJV}}</ref>\n\n===Islam===\n[[File:Rebabah.jpg|thumb|[[Transjordanian]] [[Bedouin]] with shoulder length hair, during [[World War II]]]]\nIn the Muslim world, it seems the trend of hair styles is now favouring short over long in men. In the past, Bedouin Muslims often wore their hair in long braids, but influences from the Western world have caused a change in attitudes. Bedouins are now less likely to have long hair.<ref>{{Citation |last=Massad |first=Joseph |title=Colonial Effects |location=New York |publisher=Columbia University Press |year=2001 |isbn=0-231-12322-1 |pages=137\u2013140, 208\u2013210}}</ref> Islamic countries in [[North Africa]] such as [[Egypt]] view long hair in men as modernist and in one case the Egyptian police viewed it as Satanic and a sign of an infidel.<ref>{{Citation |last=Heper |first=Metin |title=Ismet Inonu: the Making of a Turkish Statesman |location=Boston |publisher=Brill Academic Publishers |year=1998 |page=153 |isbn=90-04-09919-0}}</ref> Spanish rulers during the [[Medieval Period]] suspected long-haired males to be Moors or Moriscos, therefore long hair was forbidden since it was believed to be a Moorish custom. However, modern North African men have adopted Western short hair.\n\nMuslims regard the [[Prophet Muhammad]] as the best example to live by, and try to emulate him whenever possible. The Islamic [[Prophet Muhammad]] reportedly in [[Sahih Muslim]] had hair that \"hung over his shoulders and earlobes\".<ref>[[Sahih Muslim]] Book 30 Number 5773: \"Qatada reported: I asked Anas b. Malik: How was the hair of Allah's Messenger? Thereupon he said: His hair was neither very curly nor very straight, and they hung over his shoulders and earlobes.\"</ref> [[Sahih Bukhari]], regarded the most authentic of [[hadith]], also supports this using a prime example of the prophet [[Jesus in Islam|Isa]] (Jesus).<ref>[[Sahih Al-Bukhari]] Volume 7 Book 72 Number 788: \"Narrated Al-Bara':\nI did not see anybody in a red cloak looking more handsome than the Prophet Narrated Malik: The hair of the Prophet used to hang near his shoulders. Narrated Shu'ba: The hair of the Prophet used to hang down to the earlobes.\"</ref> The Prophet Muhammad has also described Jesus as \"having long hair reaching his ear lobes.\"<ref>Sahih Al-Bukhari Volume 9 Book 87 Number 128 : Narrated 'Abdullah bin 'Umar: Allah's Apostle said, \"I saw myself (in a dream) near the Ka'ba last night, and I saw a man with whitish red complexion, the best you may see amongst men of that complexion having long hair reaching his earlobes which was the best hair of its sort, and he had combed his hair and water was dropping from it, and he was performing the Tawaf around the Ka'ba while he was leaning on two men or on the shoulders of two men. I asked, 'Who is this man?' Somebody replied, '(He is) Messiah, son of Mary.' Then I saw another man with very curly hair, blind in the right eye which looked like a protruding out grape. I asked, 'Who is this?' Somebody replied, '(He is) Messiah, Ad-Dajjal.'\"</ref> Malik's Muwatta 51.2.6 reported, Yahya related to me from Malik from Yahya ibn Said that Abu Qatada al-Ansari said to the Messenger of Allah, may Allah bless him and grant him peace, \"I have a lot of hair which comes down to my shoulders, shall I comb it?'' The Messenger of Allah, may Allah bless him and grant him peace, said, \"Yes, and honour it.\" Sometimes Abu Qatada oiled it twice in one day because the Messenger of Allah, may Allah bless him and grant him peace, said to him. \"Honour it.\"\n\nWith regards to women, neither Qur'an nor Sunnah explicitly state that women cannot cut their hair. Hadith does mention that women should not imitate men, and vice versa, and hence many scholars on this assumption, decree that women should let their hair grow longer than the hair of the Prophet, reaching beyond their shoulders, as hadith mentions that the Prophet had his hair between his shoulder and his earlobes. (He described Jesus's hair, which hung to his earlobes, as long.<ref>Sahih Al-Bukhari Volume 9 Book 87 Number 128</ref>)\n\nHowever, according to some hadiths regarding the rules of [[awrah]], women are required to grow hair long, long enough that it would cover the breasts or as much awrah parts of the body when they're being buried, because she lacks clothes and long hair would be used as a covering instead.\n\nSome Muslims are also opposed to men having long hair as it is also important in Islam to have clear differences (in appearance) between sexes. And generally these cultures encourage women to have long hair and men to have short hair.<ref name = islam>{{Citation |last1=Joseph |first1=Suad |first2=Afsaneh |last2=Najmabadi |authorlink2=Afsaneh Najmabadi |title=Encyclopedia of Women & Islamic Cultures: Family, Body, Sexuality and Health, Volume 3 |location=Boston |publisher=Brill Academic Publishers |year=2005 |page=35 |isbn=90-04-12819-0}}</ref> The [[Taliban]] in Afghanistan viewed long hair for men as a western influence, and punished it by arrest and forced haircuts,<ref name = taliban>{{Citation |last=Rashid |first=Ahmed |title=Taliban: Islam, oil and the new great game in central Asia |publisher=I B Tauris & Co Ltd |year=2002 |page=219 |isbn=1-86064-830-4}}</ref> although this would be a direct contradiction of the [[sunnah]] of the Prophet. Similar measures have been taken by Islamists in [[Iraq]].<ref>{{Citation |first=Sudarsan |last=Raghavan |journal=The Washington Post |date=2006-10-06 |url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/15149242/ |title=Another freedom cut short: Iraq's barbers under threat |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080725055030/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/15149242/ |archivedate=2008-07-25 |access-date=2009-05-19 }}</ref> In spite of this, several Taliban affiliated members of the [[Mehsud]] clan are recognisable by their long hair.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/3745962.stm |title=South Asia &#124; Profile: Abdullah Mehsud |publisher=BBC News |date=2007-07-24 |accessdate=2013-10-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/pakistan/7672214/Taliban-leader-Hakimullah-Mehsud-threatens-US-months-after-death.html |title=Taliban leader Hakimullah Mehsud threatens US months after 'death' |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=2010-05-03 |accessdate=2013-10-27}}</ref> The [[Saudi people|Saudi]] Islamist fighter [[Amir Khattab]] was also notable for his long hair. [[Dervishes]] of some [[Sufi]] orders, such as the [[Kasnazani]], often have long hair and whirl it around during rituals.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/21/world/africa/21iht-sufis.html | work=The New York Times | first=Edward | last=Wong | title=Iraq's Sufis attacked as strife widens | date=2005-08-22}}</ref>\n\n===Sikhism===\nFor [[Sikhs]], [[Kesh (Sikhism)|Kesh]] is the practice of allowing one's hair to grow naturally as a symbol of devotion to God and lack of worldliness.<ref name = fowler>{{cite book |last=Fowler |first=Jeaneane |title=World Religions: an Introduction for Students |location=Brighton |publisher=Sussex Academic Press |year=1997 |page=[https://archive.org/details/worldreligionsin0000unse/page/352 352] |isbn=1-898723-48-6 |url=https://archive.org/details/worldreligionsin0000unse/page/352 }}</ref>\n{{Unreferenced section|date=August 2014}}\n\nThe Sikhs were commanded by Guru Gobind Singh at the Baisakhi Amrit Sanchar in 1699 to wear long uncut hair called [[Kesh (Sikhism)|Kesh]] at all times to signify the strength and vitality of the Sikh people. This was one of the 'five requisites of faith', collectively called Kakars that form the external visible identifiers to clearly affirm a Sikh's commitment and dedication to the order (Hukam) of the tenth master and made one a member of the Khalsa. The Khalsa is the \"Saint-Soldier\" of Guru Gobind Singh who stated the following:\n\"He does not recognize anyone else except One Lord, not even the bestowal of charities, performance of merciful acts, austerities and restraint on pilgrim-stations; the perfect light of the Lord illuminates his heart, then consider him as the immaculate Khalsa.\" (Guru Gobind Singh in the Dasam Granth page 1350)\n\nThe Kesh or unshorn long hair is an indispensable part of the human body as created by waheguru that is the mainstay of the 'Jivan Jaach' and the Rehni that was prescribed by Guru Gobind Singh Sahib by which a Sikh is clearly and quickly identified, Kesh. The kanga, another requisite of faith is usually tucked behind the \"Rishi Knot\" and tied under the turban. The uncut long head hair and the beard in the case of men forms the main kakar for the Sikhs.\n\nKESADHARI, a term defining a Sikh as one who carries on his head the full growth of his kes (hair) which he never trims or cuts for any reason. Anyone, Sikh or non-Sikh, may keep the hair unshorn, but for the Sikh kes, unshorn hair, is a requisite of faith and an inviolable vow. The Sikh Rahit Maryada published by the Shiromani Gurdwara Prabandhak Committee, statutory body for the control and management of Sikh shrines and by extension for laying down rules about Sikh beliefs and practices, issued in 1945, after long and minute deliberations among Sikh scholars and theologians, defines a Sikh thus:\nEvery Sikh who has been admitted to the rites of amrit, i.e. who has been initiated as a Sikh, must allow his hair to grow to its full length. This also applies to those born of Sikh families but [who] have not yet received the rites of amrit of the tenth master, Guru Gobind Singh.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Personal grooming|Grooming]]\n*[[Haircut]]\n*[[Hair extensions]]\n*[[Hair stick]]\n*[[Lady Godiva]]\n*[[Long hair fetishism]], a form of ''Trichophilia''\n*[[Rapunzel]]\n\n==Images==\n*[[commons:Category:Female long hair in art|Female long hair in art]] (Gallery at Wikimedia commons)\n*[[commons:Category:Female long hair|Female long hair photos]] (Gallery at Wikimedia commons)\n*[[commons:Category:Male long hair in art|Male long hair in art]] (Gallery at Wikimedia commons)\n*[[commons:Category:Male long hair|Male long hair photos]] (Gallery at Wikimedia commons)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book |ref=Byrd |last1=Byrd |first1=Ayana |first2=Lori |last2=Tharps |title=Hair Story |location=New York |publisher=St. Martin's Griffin |year=2002 |isbn=0-312-28322-9 |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780312283223 }}\n\n==External links==\n* {{commons category-inline}}\n* {{Wiktionary-inline}}\n\n{{Human hair}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Long Hair}}\n[[Category:Hairstyles]]\n[[Category:Pejorative terms for people]]\n[[Category:Heavy metal fashion]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|human head hair|other uses|Longhair (disambiguation)}}\n[[File:Wenceslas Hollar - Young man with long hair (State 1).jpg|230px|right|thumb|A man with shoulder length hair, 1599]]\n[[File:KonkanaBakshi.jpg|250px|right|thumb|A woman with waist length hair]]\n'''Long hair''' is a [[hairstyle]] where the [[head hair]] is allowed to grow to a considerable length. Exactly what constitutes long hair can change from culture to culture, or even within cultures. For example, a woman with chin-length hair in some cultures may be said to have short hair, while a man with the same length of hair in some of the same cultures would be said to have long hair.\n\nMales having short, cut hair are in many cultures viewed as being under society's control, such as while in the military or prison or as punishment for a crime. Long lustrous female hair is generally rated [[Physical attractiveness|attractive]] by both men and women across cultures.<ref>{{cite book|first=David M. |last=Buss|title=The handbook of evolutionary psychology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=esDW3xTKoLIC&pg=PA309 |year=2005|publisher=John Wiley and Sons|isbn=978-0-471-26403-3|page=309}}</ref><ref name=\"Bereczkei\">{{cite journal|author=Bereczkei, T. |title=Hair length, facial attractiveness, personality attribution; A multiple fitness model of hairdressing|journal=Review of Psychology|volume=13|issue=1 |year=2007|pages=35\u201342|url=http://hrcak.srce.hr/9060?lang=en}}</ref> The prevalence of [[trichophilia]] (hair partialism or [[fetishism]]) is 7% in the population, and very long hair is a common subject of devotion in this group.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Scorolli | first1 = C | last2 = Ghirlanda | first2 = S | last3 = Enquist | first3 = M | last4 = Zattoni | first4 = S | last5 = Jannini | first5 = E A | title = Relative prevalence of different fetishes | journal = International Journal of Impotence Research | volume = 19 | issue = 4 | pages = 432\u20137 | year = 2007 | pmid = 17304204 | doi = 10.1038/sj.ijir.3901547 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hairstylenation.com/heels-top-global-fetish-leaderboard/ |location=England |title=Heels top the global fetish leader board |access-date=2014-07-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714113006/http://www.hairstylenation.com/heels-top-global-fetish-leaderboard/ |archive-date=2014-07-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Biological significance==\n[[File:\u80cc\u4e2d (10675203514) (cropped).jpg|right|thumb|A woman with mid-back level hair]]\nHumans, [[horse]]s, [[orangutan]]s and [[lion]]s are among the few species that may grow their head hair or [[wikt:mane|mane]]s very long. Humans are believed to have lost their fur 2.5\u20133 million years ago as [[hominid]]s when transitioning from a forest habitat to the open savanna, as an effect of [[natural selection]], since this development made it possible to run fast and hunt animals close to the equator without getting overheated. Head hair was an exception, which was a survival trait because it provides [[thermal insulation]] of the scalp from the sun, protects against [[Ultraviolet|ultraviolet radiation]] exposure(UV), and also provides cooling (when sweat evaporates from soaked hair).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.philpoteducation.com/mod/book/tool/print/index.php?id=783&chapterid=1038|title=2.2 Applications and skills|website=www.philpoteducation.com|access-date=2019-11-07}}</ref> The ability to grow [[straight hair]] has been observed among [[Homo sapiens]] sub-groups in less sunny regions further away from the equator. Relative to kinked [[Afro-textured hair]], straight hair allows more UV light to pass to the scalp (which is essential for the production of vitamin D, that is important for bone development<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/figure/The-role-of-ARA-in-bone-development-and-homeostatic-regulation-of-vitamin-D3-and_fig3_301247535|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>).\n\nScientists also view the ability to grow very long hair as a result of [[sexual selection]], since long and healthy hair is a sign of fertility and youth.<ref name = watson>{{cite book |last=Watson |first=James |title=Darwin: the Indelible Stamp; the Evolution of an Idea |location=Philadelphia |publisher=Running Press |year=2005 |page=[https://archive.org/details/indeliblestampev00darw/page/1042 1042] |isbn=0-7624-2136-3 |url=https://archive.org/details/indeliblestampev00darw/page/1042 }}</ref>{{quotation needed|date=December 2012}} An [[evolutionary biology]] explanation for this attraction is that hair length and quality can act as a cue to youth and health, signifying a woman's reproductive potential.<ref name=Hinsz/> As hair grows slowly, long hair may reveal 2\u20133 years of a person's health status, nutrition, age and reproductive fitness. Malnutrition, and deficiencies in minerals and vitamins due to starvation, cause loss of hair or changes in hair color (e.g. dark hair turning reddish).<ref name=EPHandbook2005>Sugiyama, Lawrence S. (2005) \"Physical Attractiveness in Adaptationist Perspective\", Chapter 10 in Buss, David M. (ed.) ''The Handbook of Evolutionary Psychology''. John Wiley & Sons, Inc. {{ISBN|978-0-471-26403-3}}</ref>\n\n==Psychological significance==\n[[Anthropologists]] speculate that the functional significance of long head hair may be [[adornment]], a by-product of secondary [[natural selection]] once other [[androgenic hair|androgenic]]/[[Somatic (biology)|somatic]] hair (body hair) had largely been lost. Another possibility is that long head hair is a result of [[Fisherian runaway]] [[sexual selection]], where long lustrous hair is a visible [[Genetic marker|marker]] for a healthy individual. For some groups or individuals, however, short hair is the selected trait.<ref name = watson/>\n\nBy seven to nine months, infants can tell the sexes apart based on hair length, voice pitch, and faces.<ref>{{cite book |first1=Simon Johnson |last1=Williams |first2=Lynda I. A. |last2=Birke |first3=Gillian |last3=Bendelow |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xrK15NBbYQcC&pg=PA130|title=Debating biology: sociological reflections on health, medicine, and society |page=130 |publisher=Routledge |year=2003 |isbn=0-415-27903-8}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural meaning==\nWays of life often viewed as more rigid, such as soldiering and religious discipline, frequently have explicit rules regarding hair length. For example, Buddhist monks shave their heads as part of their order of worship.<ref name = leach>{{cite journal|last=Leach |first=E. R. |authorlink=Edmund Leach |title=Magical Hair |journal=Journal of the Royal Anthropological Institute |date=July 1958 |volume=88 |issue=2 |pages=147\u2013164 |doi=10.2307/2844249|jstor=2844249 }}</ref> Similarly, religious men with long hair include the [[Nazarites]] of the [[Hebrew Bible]] ([[Samson]] being a famous example)<ref name = judge/> and the [[Sikh]]s.<ref name = fowler/> Subservient cultures may view male long hair negatively, and are sometimes detected by their rulers through hair length, as was the case with the [[Gaelic Ireland|Gaelic Irish]] under English rule and the [[Reconquista|Moors under Spanish rule]] in [[Medieval]] [[Spain]].{{clarify|date=July 2014}}\n\nEast Asian cultures have traditionally associated unkempt hair in a woman with irresponsible attitude, as women in East Asia were expected to tie up their hair in styles such as the ponytail, plait, or any bun, as a symbol of responsibility.<ref name = asia/>\n\n==Transferred meaning==\nThe traditional connotation of \"long hair\" in [[English language|English]] meant, roughly, someone artistically knowledgeable or wise, an [[aesthete]].<ref name = OED>[[Oxford English Dictionary]]</ref> As a descriptive term, it has been applied to [[Merovingian dynasty|Merovingians]] and [[classical music]] enthusiasts, as well as [[hippie]]s and aesthetes.<ref name = OED/>\n\n==Hair lengths==\n<gallery widths=\"150\" heights=\"200\">\nFile:Girl with long black hair, rear view (1 November 2018).jpg|An Indonesian woman with shoulder length hair\nFile:Tracy E Caldwell portrait.jpg|The American astronaut [[Tracy Caldwell Dyson|Tracy Caldwell]] with armpit length hair\nFile:Apocalyptica Drive With Full Force 2018 20.jpg|Finnish cello player [[Perttu Kivilaakso]] with mid back length hair\nFile:\u80cc\u4e2d (2828530544).jpg|A Japanese woman with waist length hair\nFile:\" 12 - ITALY - FIAT - Girls at Bologna Motorshow 2012 01.jpg|An Italian woman with hip/tailbone length hair\nFile:Very long hair woman and her friend Sri Lanka.jpg|A Sri Lankan woman with classic length hair\nFile:Yungchen Lhamo.jpeg|A Tibetan woman with knee length hair\n</gallery>\n\nHair length is most often measured (in centimeters or inches) from the line of the [[scalp]] on the [[forehead]] up over the highest point of the skull to its termination, and sometimes from the crown, the latter resulting in 10 centimeter lower values in average.<ref name=\"Scalp-hair-length-II\"/> In [[cosmetology]], hair lengths are usually categorized according to the part of the body where the bulk of the longest hair terminates: ''chin level'', ''shoulder length'', ''lower shoulderblade''/''mid-back level'', ''waist length'', ''hip-length'', ''classic length'' (extends to almost ''buttock-length'', i.e. upper thigh-length, where the [[Human leg|legs]] meet the [[buttocks]]), ''thigh-length'', ''knee-length'' and ''ankle/floor length'' hair.<ref name=\"Scalp-hair-length-II\"/><ref name=cosmetology>{{cite book |first=Anthony |last=Gonzalez |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dKVBDlaGoAAC&pg=PT54 |title=Cosmetology |page=54 |publisher=Global Media |year=2007 |isbn=81-89940-45-7}}</ref>\n\nHair usually takes about two years to reach shoulder length,<ref name=Andropathy/> and about seven years to reach waist-length/hip-length, including occasional trims (approximately 80\u201390&nbsp;cm (32\u201336&nbsp;inches) from forehead for most people)<ref name=cosmetology/><ref name=Andropathy>{{cite book |first=R. A. S. |last=Hemat |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r1jCtGD4CcsC&pg=PA375 |title=Andropathy |page=375 |publisher=Urotext |year=2007 |isbn=1-903737-08-7}}</ref>\n\n===Maximum hair length===\n[[File:Pierre Auguste Renoir - Portrait de Julie Manet.jpg|210px|right|thumb|Portrait of Julie Manet by [[Pierre-Auguste Renoir|Renoir]], 1894]]\nThe maximum hair length that is possible to reach is about 15&nbsp;cm (6&nbsp;in) for infants (below the age of 1), about 60&nbsp;cm (24&nbsp;in) for children, and generally 100&nbsp;cm (40&nbsp;in) for adults. Documentation for decrease of the maximum length with age cannot be found in the literature. Some individuals can reach excessive lengths. Lengths greater than 150&nbsp;cm (59&nbsp;in) are frequently observed in long hair contests.<ref name=Robbins>{{cite book |first=Clarence R. |last=Robbins |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-UTEKeEypjEC&pg=PA11|title=Chemical and physical behavior of human hair |publisher=Springer |year=2002 |isbn=0-387-95094-X}}</ref> [[Xie Qiuping]] had the longest documented hair in the world, measuring 5.627 m (18&nbsp;ft 5.54 in) in May 2004.<ref>[http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/dedication/longest-hair-(female) Guinness World Records: Longest hair]. guinnessworldrecords.com</ref>\n\nThe maximum [[terminal hair]] length depends on the length of the [[Anagen phase|anagen]] (period of hair growth) for the individual. Waist-length hair or longer is only possible to reach for people with long anagen. The anagen lasts between 2 and 7 years, for some individuals even longer, and is followed by shorter [[catagen]] (transition) and [[telogen]] (resting) periods. At any given time, about 85% of hair strands are in anagen.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Principles of Anatomy & Physiology |edition=13 |author=Tortora & Derrickson |publisher=John Wiley & Sons, Inc |date=2012 |page=163}}</ref> The [[fibroblast growth factor 5]] (FGF5) gene affects the hair cycle in mammals including humans; blocking FGF5 in the human scalp (by applying a herbal extract that blocked FGF5) extends the hair cycle, resulting in less hair fall and increased hair growth.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.2336/nishinihonhifu.69.81| title = Sanguisorba Officinalis Root Extract Has FGF-5 Inhibitory Activity and Reduces Hair Loss by Causing Prolongation of the Anagen Period| journal = Nishi Nihon Hifuka| volume = 69| pages = 81| year = 2007| last1 = Maeda | first1 = T. | last2 = Yamamoto | first2 = T. | last3 = Isikawa | first3 = Y. | last4 = Itoh | first4 = N. | last5 = Arase | first5 = S. }}</ref>\n\n==Cultural history==\n\n===Europe===\n\n====Ancient Greece and Rome====\n[[File:Bust of Zeus.jpg|thumb|[[Ancient Rome|Roman]] marble colossal head of a long-haired [[Zeus]], 2nd century AD.]]\nIn [[ancient Greece]], long male hair was a symbol of wealth and power, while a shaven head was appropriate for a slave. The ancient Greeks had several gods and heroes who wore their hair long, including [[Zeus]], [[Achilles]], [[Apollo]], and [[Poseidon]]. Greek soldiers are said to have worn their hair long in battle. Such warriors considered it a sign of aristocracy and are said to have combed it openly in order to show off.  Also, in order to keep enemies from getting a hold of it in battle, they were known to cut the front short, but leave it long in the back, where it was more out of reach ([[Mullet (haircut)|mullet]]). A widely held alternative interpretation of the conventional belief is that they kept it long, and simply tied it back in a style known as a [[ponytail]] in order to keep it out of their enemies' reach. The ponytail method allowed warriors, who often traveled to battle with a minimal amount of equipment in order to avoid excessively heavy loads over long marches, to keep their hair manageable with a small piece of string to hold their pony tail in place and a knife to cut the back to length with one simple slice. Around the sixth century, however, the Greek men shifted to shorter hairstyles, with the exception of the Spartans. Women in the culture remained with the longer style, which for them showed freedom, health, and wealth, as well as good behavior.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Irwin |first=M. Eleanor |title=Odysseus' \"Hyacinthine Hair\" in 'Odyssey' 6.231 |journal=Phoenix |date=Oct 1990 |volume=44 |issue=3 |pages=205\u2013218 |doi=10.2307/1088933|jstor=1088933 }}</ref> In men, long hair was considered a sign of false pride by this time.<ref name = barbers>{{cite journal |last=Nicolson |first=Frank W. |title=Greek and Roman Barbers |journal=Harvard Studies in Classical Philology |year=1891 |volume=2 |pages=41\u201356|url=https://archive.org/details/jstor-310326|jstor=310326}}</ref>\n\n[[Pliny the Elder]] in his ''[[Natural History (Pliny)|Natural History]]'' and [[Varro]] related that the Romans did not begin to cut their hair short until barbers were introduced to Italy from Sicily by P. Ticinius Mena in 299 BC.<ref>[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.02.0137%3Abook%3D7%3Achapter%3D59 Pliny the Elder at Perseus]</ref> Women in Roman times valued long hair, usually with a center part. Apart from in the earliest times, men's hair was usually shorter than women's, although other cultures of the time, such as Greeks in the east, considered long hair to be typical of philosophers, who were thought to be too engrossed in learning to bother with hair.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Bartman |first=Elizabeth |title=Hair and the Artifice of Roman Female Adornment |journal=American Journal of Archaeology |date=Jan 2001 |volume=105 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201325 |jstor=507324}}</ref> Strictly in the province of Rome, however, the shorter hairstyle was especially popular.<ref name = barbers/> When Julius Caesar conquered the [[Gauls]], who favored long hair, he ordered it to be cut short.<ref>{{cite book |last=Felt |first=Joseph |title=Customs of New England |location=New York |publisher=Burt Franklin |year=1967 |page=187 |isbn=0-8337-1105-9}}</ref>\n\n====Middle Ages====\nIn the European [[middle ages]], shorter hair often signified servitude and peasantry, while long hair was often attributed to freemen, as was the case with the Germanic [[Goths]] and [[Merovingians]].\n\nThe [[Gaelic Ireland|Gaelic Irish]] (both men and women)<ref name=\"Connolly-prologue\">{{cite book |title=Contested island: Ireland 1460\u20131630 |last=Connolly |first=Sean J |year=2007 |publisher=Oxford University Press |page=7 |chapter=Prologue}}</ref> took great pride in their long hair\u2014for example, a person could be heavily fined for cutting a man's hair short against his will.<ref name=\"Ginnell7\">[http://www.libraryireland.com/Brehon-Laws/Contents.php ''The Brehon Laws: A Legal Handbook: Chapter VII''], Laurence Ginnell (1894)</ref> When the Anglo-Normans and the English colonized Ireland, hair length came to signify one's allegiance. Irishmen who cut their hair short were deemed to be forsaking their Irish heritage. Likewise, English colonists who wore their hair long in the back were deemed to be forsaking their role as English subjects and giving in to the Irish life. Thus, hair length was one of the most common ways of judging a true Englishman in this period.  Muslims in Christian areas were ordered to keep their hair short and parted, as their longer style was considered rebellious and barbaric.<ref name = ma>{{cite journal|last=Bartlett |first=Robert |title=Symbolic Meanings of Hair in the Middle Ages |journal=Transactions of the Royal Historical Society |year=1994 |series=Sixth series |volume=4 |pages=43\u201360|doi=10.2307/3679214|jstor=3679214 }}</ref>\n[[File:Empress Elisabeth of Austria.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Empress Elisabeth of Austria]] wearing thigh-length hair in 1865. (Painting by [[Franz Xaver Winterhalter]])]]\n\nThe long hair tradition was widespread among English and French men in the 11th and 12th centuries, though it was considered, mostly because of endorsement of the [[Roman Catholic Church]], acceptable for men also to have shorter hair.  The tradition was largely brought about by monarchs who rejected the shorter hairstyle, causing the people to follow. [[Wulfstan (died 1023)|Wulfstan]], a religious leader, worried that those with longer hair would fight like women, and be unable to protect England from foreign invasion. This idea can be found in later military leaders as well, such as those of the [[Confederate States of America|American Confederacy]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Battle of Cloids Mountain of Virginia, 1864|last=McManus|first=Howard Rollins|publisher=University of Michigan|year=1989|isbn=|page=35}}<!--ISBN 0-930919-89-0?--></ref> Knights and rulers would also sometimes cut or pull out their hair in order to show penitence and mourning, and a squire's hair was generally shorter than a knight's. Married women who let their hair flow out in public were frowned upon, as this was normally reserved for the unwed, although they were allowed to let it out in mourning, to show their distressed state. Through these centuries it was expected of [[Eastern Christian]]s to wear long hair as well as long beards, which was especially expected from clergy and monks.\n\nIn England, during the [[English Civil War]]s of 1642 to 1651, male hair length was emblematic of the disputes between [[Cavaliers]] and [[Roundheads]] (Puritans).  Cavaliers wore longer hair, and were less religious-minded, thought of by the Roundheads as lecherous.  The more devout Roundheads typically had somewhat shorter hair.<ref name = leach/>\n\nAround this time, long hair in England also came to be associated with adventurers who traveled to America and were familiar with the native culture there, short hair with less adventurous types.\n\n====Trends among women in 20th and 21st centuries====\n<gallery widths=\"150\" heights=\"200\">\nFile:The Seven Sutherland Sisters.jpg|The Seven Sutherland Sisters were singing and showing off their famous floor-length hair in a sideshow of Barnum & Bailey's from about 1882 to 1907.\nFile:Mary_Garden_in_Debussy%27s_Pell%C3%A9as_et_M%C3%A9lisande_2.jpg|Opera singer [[Mary Garden]] in 1908 with knee-length hair\nFile:Dewi-persik.jpg|[[Dewi Persik]] with waist-length hair\nFile:Woman with very long hair.JPG|[[Dutch people|Dutch]] woman with thigh-length hair\nFile:TweiMadchen vonSangaflussCentralafrika.jpg|[[Ngbandi people|Ngbandi]] girls with hip-length hair\n</gallery>\n\nGrowing and wearing long hair was common among women in the Western world until World War One.<ref name = cosmetology/> Long female hair never ceased in western culture, though it was rare during the 1920s and 1930s.\n\nIn most current cultures, it is more typical for women to wear long hair than for men to do so. An American study shows significant correlation between hair length and age, which indicates that younger women tend to have longer hair than older women. A significant correlation was also found between women's hair length and hair quality. Moreover, hair quality was correlated with the women's perceived physical health. Consistent with principles of [[evolutionary psychology]], these results indicate that hair length and quality can act as a cue to a woman's youth and health, signifying reproductive potential. The correlation between the woman's hair length and marital status, or number of children, was however not more than to be expected from the correlation between hair length and age.<ref name=Hinsz>{{cite journal |first1=Verlin B. |last1=Hinsz |first2=David C. |last2=Matz |first3=Rebecca A. |last3=Patience |title=Does women's hair signal reproductive potential? |journal=Journal of Experimental Social Psychology|year=2001 |volume=37 |issue=2 |page=166 |doi=10.1006/jesp.2000.1450}}</ref>\n\n====Trends among men in 20th and 21st centuries====\n[[File:Aankomst Beatles op Schiphol, de Beatles tijdens persconferentie John Lennon, Bestanddeelnr 916-5131.jpg|thumb|Long male hair in western youth culture became popular in the 1960s and 70s with [[The Beatles]].]]\n[[File:Bob-Marley-in-Concert Zurich 05-30-80.jpg|thumb|[[Bob Marley]] made [[rastafari]] culture and [[dreadlocks]] popular also outside [[Jamaica]].]]\n[[File:Black Sabbath, original lineup (1973).JPG|thumb|[[Black Sabbath]]. A long hair is very popular in [[Heavy metal subculture]].]]\nBefore World War One men generally had longer hair and beards. However, short hair on men was introduced in World War One for soldiers. Slaves and defeated armies were often required to shave their heads. The [[trench warfare]] in 1914 to 1918 exposed men to [[flea]] and [[lice infestations]], which prompted the order to cut hair short, establishing a military tradition.<ref name = cosmetology/>\n\nBeat poets during the 1950s wore longer hairstyles. By 1960, a small \"[[beatnik]]\" community in [[Newquay]], Cornwall, England (including a young [[Wizz Jones]]) had attracted the attention of their neighbors for growing their hair to a length past the shoulders, resulting in a television interview with [[Alan Whicker]] on BBC television's ''[[Tonight (1957 TV series)|Tonight]]'' series.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W3WfXA9JL9w Whicker, Alan. ''Tonight'': \"Beatniks in Newquay\". BBC, 1960.]</ref> The 1960s also introduced [[The Beatles]], who started a more widespread longer hair trend. The [[social revolution]] of the 1960s led to a renaissance of unchecked hair growth,<ref name = cosmetology/> and long hair, especially on men, was worn as a political or [[Counterculture of the 1960s|countercultural]] symbol or protest and as a symbol of masculinity. This cultural symbol extended to several Western countries in the Americas, Western Europe, South Africa, and Australia.<ref name = gay>{{Citation |last=Bronski |first=Michael |title=The Pleasure Principle: Sex, Backlash, and the Struggle for Gay Freedom |publisher=Stonewall Inn Editions |year=2000 |pages=95\u201396 |isbn=0-312-25287-0}}</ref> Specific long hairstyles such as [[dreadlocks]] have been part of counterculture movements seeking to define other alternative cultures and lifestyles since this time.<ref name=\"asia\"/> Longer hair in general remained popular due to the youth rebellion throughout the liberal decade of the 1960s.<ref name = gay/> The long hair trend grew with the spread of the [[hippie]] movement in the 1960s<ref name = gay/> and, in the 1970s, longer hair styles would become the norm among men and women.\n\nIn the 1970s, the popularity of [[Jamaica]]'s [[reggae]] music and musician [[Bob Marley]] prompted interest in [[dreadlocks]] internationally. The anti-establishment philosophy of [[Rastafari movement|Rastafari]], echoed in much of the reggae of the time, resonated with left-leaning youth of all ethnicities \u2013 especially and primarily among [[African American]]s and other [[Black people|Blacks]], but among [[counterculture]] [[Whites]] as well.<ref>{{Citation |last1=Gossai |first1=Hemchand |first2=Nathaniel |last2=Murrell |title=Religion, Culture, and Tradition in the Caribbean |location=New York |publisher=St. Martin's Press |year=2000 |pages=181\u2013190 |isbn=0-312-23242-X}}</ref> [[Eastern Christian]]s are encouraged {{By whom|date=June 2017}} to wear long hair with long beard. In the 1980s the view of long hair as a solitary signifier of political or counter-cultural identity was countered and parodied in films such as [[Rambo (film series)|Rambo]] and many other militaristic heroes of media which challenged then-contemporary views of tradition.<ref>{{Citation |last=Lu |first=Hsiao-Peng |title=Transnational Chinese Cinemas |location=Honolulu |publisher=University of Hawaii Press |year=1997 |page=[https://archive.org/details/transnationalchi0000unse/page/229 229] |isbn=0-8248-1845-8 |url=https://archive.org/details/transnationalchi0000unse/page/229 }}</ref> In the 2000s longer hairstyles among men became popular among neopagans and [[rock music|rock]] enthusiasts;<ref>{{Citation |last=Weinstein |first=Deena |title=Heavy Metal |location=New York |publisher=Da Capo Press |year=2000 |page=129 |isbn=0-306-80970-2}}</ref> for example, musicians in [[heavy metal music|metal]] bands and their fans often wear long hair. Long hair may be grown for the purpose of being [[donate]]d to an [[organization]], such as [[Locks of Love]], for [[hairpiece]]s to help those who could not have hair otherwise, such as those who are diagnosed with [[alopecia areata]]. Today long hair has gained even more popularity. Even among mainstream men it is socially acceptable to have hair reaching around the upper back. This could in part be due to the \"man bun\" trend where men pull their shoulder length or longer hair back into a topknot [[Bun (hairstyle)|bun]].\n\n===Americas===\n====Native Americans====\n[[File:Yakima boy.png|thumb|right|[[Yakama people|Yakima]] boy with ''mid-back level'' hair. (Photo by [[Edward S. Curtis]], 1868\u20131952.)]]\nMany [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] men wore long hair before the arrival of western influences on their culture. (In Cherokee legends, for example, males said to be handsome were often described as having \"long hair almost to the ground\" or similar formulas.<ref>{{cite web |last=Kirk |first=Lowell |title=Cherokee Myths and Legends |year=1999 |url=http://www.telliquah.com/cherokee.htm |accessdate =2007-09-09 }}</ref>). Both men and women of these cultures have frequently struggled to maintain their tradition but have faced heavy opposition. Many consider it a sign of giving in to western influences to have their hair cut.<ref>{{Citation |last=Ferris |first=Jeri |title=Native American Doctor |location=Minneapolis |publisher=Carolrhoda Books |year=1991 |pages=32\u201333 |isbn=0-87614-443-1}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |last=Kilcup |first=Karen |title=Native American Women's Writing, C. 1800\u20131924 |location=Cambridge |publisher=Blackwell Publishers |year=2000 |pages=314\u2013316 |isbn=0-631-20518-7}}</ref> Early American settlers saw long-haired, native men as rebelling against their civilized society. Mountain men and trappers who adopted the customs were also considered amoral, and often identified by their long hair.<ref>{{Citation |last=Cavallo |first=Dominick |title=A Fiction of the past |location=New York |publisher=St. Martin's Press |year=1999 |page=[https://archive.org/details/fictionofpastsix00cava/page/90 90] |isbn=0-312-23501-1 |url=https://archive.org/details/fictionofpastsix00cava/page/90 }}</ref> Since the cultural movements of the Sixties and Seventies, however, Native Americans have felt less pressure to have short hair, as different movements have defended their cultural rights.<ref>{{Citation |last=Nagel |first=Joane |title=American Indian Ethnic Renewal |location=Oxford Oxfordshire |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=1997 |page=[https://archive.org/details/americanindianet0000nage/page/191 191] |isbn=0-19-512063-9 |url=https://archive.org/details/americanindianet0000nage/page/191 }}</ref> For example, several states have loosened prison regulations, allowing Native Americans to wear long hair during incarceration, along with other cultural allowances.<ref>{{Citation |last=French |first=Laurence |title=Native American Justice |location=Lanham |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers, Inc |year=2003 |pages=113\u2013117 |isbn=0-8304-1575-0}}</ref> There has been resistance to these changes, however, as long hair is sometimes used to hide drugs, as well as to identify with a gang.<ref>{{Citation |last=Fontana |first=Vincent |title=Municipal Liability |publisher=Aspen Law & Business Publishers |year=2003 |pages=241\u2013242 |isbn=0-7355-1375-9}}</ref>\n\n====African Americans====\nWhen African slaves were freed in America, they struggled to reach the social status of whites. Many former slaves tried to conform their hairstyles as part of this struggle. Women, especially, felt pressure to make their hair straight, rather than keeping the tightly coiled style they had known.<ref>[[#Byrd|Byrd]], pp. 25\u201349</ref> However, during the [[civil rights movement]] of the 1950s and 1960s, African-Americans such as [[Malcolm X]] advocated hairstyles such as [[afro]]s and [[dreadlocks]], in order to embrace their race, and to return to West African roots.<ref name=\"shame\">{{cite journal|last=Synnott|first=Anthony|date=September 1987|title=Shame and Glory: A Sociology of Hair|journal=The British Journal of Sociology|volume=38|issue=3|pages=381\u2013413|doi=10.2307/590695|jstor=590695}}</ref>\n\nSocial pressures at the time were heavily influencing these Americans (women) to have, straight hair, like white people did.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Taylor, Paul C. |title=Malcolm's Conk and Danto's Colors; Or, Four Logical Petitions concerning Race, Beauty, and Aesthetics|journal=The Journal of Aesthetics and Art Criticism|year=1999|volume= 57|issue=1 |pages=16\u201320|jstor=432060|doi=10.2307/432060}}</ref> This resulted in the [[Black is beautiful]] movement, wherein African Americans wore their long natural hair, that was however, untreated and unmodified. More recently, [[hair-extensions]] have become widespread. Scholars have pointed out the continued pressure on black women to have straight smooth hair. Amelia Jones points out that dolls for children, such as [[Barbie]]s, add to this pressure, citing as an example a new, black Barbie with straight hair. Blacks, she believes, should be able to be themselves without feeling pressured to \"tame\" their hair.<ref>Jones, Amelia (2003). ''The Feminism and Visual Culture Reader''. New York: Routledge. p. 343. {{ISBN|0415267056}}</ref>\n\n====Contemporary North America====\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float: right; margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 2em; font-size: 85%; background:#c6dbf7; color:black; width:30em; max-width: 25%;\" cellspacing=\"5\"\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\n\"She, as a veil down to the slender waist,<br/>\nHer unadorned golden tresses wore<br/>\nDishevelled, but in wanton ringlets waved,<br/>\nAs the vine curls her tendrils...\"\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | \u2013 [[John Milton]]'s description of [[Eve]] in ''[[Paradise Lost]]''\n|}\n\nIn 1972, it was estimated that 24% of American women wore shoulder length hair or longer (44% of women in ages 14 to 44), meaning slightly more than 12% of men and women altogether. Similar frequency was found in 2001, when it was estimated that about 13% of the US adult population, male as well as females, has hair shoulder-length or longer, about 2.4% have hair reaching to the bottom of the shoulder blades or longer, about 0.3% have hair waist length or longer, and only about 0.017% have hair buttocks-length or longer.<ref name=\"Scalp-hair-length-I\">{{Cite journal\n | pmid = 12644859|url=http://journal.scconline.org/abstracts/cc2003/cc054n01/p00053-p00062.html\n| year = 2003\n| author1 = Robbins\n| first1 = C\n| title = Scalp hair length. I. Hair length in Florida theme parks: An approximation of hair length in the United States of America\n| journal = Journal of cosmetic science\n| volume = 54\n| issue = 1\n| pages = 53\u201362\n| last2 = Robbins\n| first2 = M. G.\n}}</ref> By [[extrapolating]] the above data and the number of hair length records, the number of people with shoulder-length hair or longer in the USA is estimated to be 27 million,  those with waist-length hair roughly 900,000, those with buttocks-length hair to be 40,000, with knee length hair to 2,000 and with ankle length hair to 70.<ref name=\"Scalp-hair-length-II\">Clarence Robbins and Marjorie Gene Robbins, [http://journal.scconline.org/pdf/cc2003/cc054n04/p00367-p00378.pdf \"Scalp hair length. II. Estimating the percentages of adults in the USA and larger populations by hari length.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217140616/http://journal.scconline.org/pdf/cc2003/cc054n04/p00367-p00378.pdf |date=2014-12-17 }} Journal of cosmetic science 54.4 (2003): 367\u2013378.</ref>\n\n===Africa===\n[[File:Halimaahmed2.jpg|thumb|right|[[Somali people|Somali]] woman with shoulder-length hair.]]\nThroughout much of Africa, [[afro-textured hair]] is the most frequent hair form, except among the [[Afro-Asiatic languages|Afro-Asiatic]] (Hamito-Semitic) speaking populations in [[North Africa]] and the [[Horn of Africa]]. In the latter regions, naturally long hair is instead more common.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hiernaux|first1=Jean|title=The People of Africa|date=1975|publisher=Scribners|isbn=0684140403|page=59|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=WJ-wAAAAIAAJ}}</ref>\n\nIn [[West Africa]]n cultures, women with long hair were highly valued. Long, thick hair was seen as a sign of health, strength, and capability to bear many children. In keeping with this general theme, women who were too young for marriage would shave a portion of their heads to signal so. This tradition, however, did not extend to every West African culture, as several valued shorter hair.<ref>[[#Byrd|Byrd]], pp. 2\u20135</ref>\n\n===Asia===\nHistorically, East Asian cultures viewed long hair as a sign of youth and aesthetic beauty. Long hair is associated with private life and sexuality. East Asian cultures see long, unkempt hair in a woman as a sign of sexual intent or a recent sexual encounter, as usually their hair is tied up.<ref name = asia>{{Citation |last=Maynard |first=Margaret |title=Dress and Globalisation |location=Manchester |publisher=Manchester University Press |year=2004 |page=104 |isbn=0-7190-6389-2}}</ref> Lay Buddhists have long hair, while Buddhist monks have shaved heads.<ref name = leach/>\n<gallery widths=\"150\" heights=\"200\">\nFile:Goyo Kamisuki.jpg|Japanese woman combing her long hair. (Colour woodblock print from 1920 by [[Hashiguchi Goy\u014d]].)\nFile:Ch5 wakamurasaki2.jpg|Illustration of [[The Tale of Genji]], painted by [[Tosa Mitsuoki]] (1617\u20131691).\nFile:Albazin Youth. Albazin Prisoners of War Professed the Orthodox Religion but Adopted Chinese Language and Customs after Capture by Manchurians in 1685. Beijing, 1874 WDL1941.png|Chinese orthodox Christian man from 1874\nFile:Nosu girls.jpg|[[Nosu]] girls in China 1922.\nFile:A hindoo fakeer with long hair.jpg|A hindoo \"[[fakir]]\" or Sadhu with long hair. Lithograph 1844 by [[Emily Eden]] after [[Lowes Cato Dickinson]].\n</gallery>\n\n====China====\nIn ancient China and Korea, hair was regarded as a precious legacy from parents. Most people would never cut their hair after they became adults, and cutting off one's hair was a penalty for minor crimes. Both men and women would coil up their hair and many hair-coiling styles were developed.\n\nBeginning in 1619, the ethnic [[Manchu]] [[Qing dynasty]] forced all men in China to adopt the [[Queue (hairstyle)|queue]]: a long braid down the back with the hair near the forehead completely shaved. Hair length and style became a life-or-death matter in 1645 as the Manchu told them either their hair or their head would be cut.\nNearly every [[Han Chinese|Han]] rebel group began by shearing this pigtail (most especially in the case of the [[Taiping Rebellion|Taiping]], who were known in Chinese as the \"Longhairs\"), but the queue on penalty of death lasted until 1911, when the Chinese people cut their queues in unison at a time of rebellion. Americans at first judged Chinese immigrant laborers to be poor workers because their long hair brought an association with women.<ref>{{Citation |last=Prasso |first=Sheridan |title=The Asian Mystique |location=New York |publisher=Public Affairs Press |year=2005 |pages=115\u2013116 |isbn=1-58648-214-9}}</ref>\n\nIslamic and Christian missionaries among the Chinese were strong advocates of shorter male hair for their converts.<ref name=\"reid\">{{cite book |last=Reid |first=Anthony |title=Southeast Asia in the Age of Commerce, 1450\u20131680 |location=New Haven |publisher=Yale University Press |year=1988 |page=82 |isbn=0-300-04750-9}}</ref> Around the Destruction of [[Four Olds]] period in 1964, almost anything seen as part of [[Culture of China|Traditional Chinese culture]] would lead to problems with the [[Communist Party of China|Communist]] [[Red Guards (China)|Red Guards]].  Items that attracted dangerous attention if caught in the public included [[jewelry]] and long male hair.<ref name=\"Law\">{{Citation |last=Law |first=Kam-yee |year=2003 |title=The Chinese Cultural Revolution Reconsidered: beyond purge and Holocaust |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |isbn=0-333-73835-7}}</ref> These things were regarded as symbols of [[bourgeois]] lifestyle, that represented wealth.  People had to avoid them or suffer serious consequences such as tortures and beatings by the guards.<ref name=\"Law\" /> More recently, long hair was ridiculed in China from October 1983 to December 1983, as part of the short and unsuccessful [[Anti-Spiritual Pollution Campaign]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Olympic crackdown on China's bad habits |publisher=BBC News |date=August 6, 2007 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/6927361.stm |accessdate = 2007-09-09 }}</ref>\n\nAlso, in Chinese ancient and modern poetry, long hair is a common [[symbol]] used by poets, for example [[Li Bai]] and [[Li Shangyin]], to express their depression and sadness.\n\n====Southeast Asia====\nIn [[Southeast Asia]] and [[Indonesia]], male long hair was valued until the seventeenth century, when the area adopted outside influences including Islam and Christianity. Invading cultures enforced shorter hairstyles on men as a sign of servitude, as well. They were also confused at the short hairstyles among women in certain areas, such as [[Thailand]], and struggled to explain why women in the area had such short hair. They came up with several mythical stories, one of which involved a king who found a long hair in his rice and, in a rage, demanded that all women keep their hair short.<ref name=\"reid\"/>\n\nIn rural areas in certain Asian countries, for example India, girls still usually let their hair grow long, and knee-length hair is not unusual.<ref name=Sherrow>Sherrow, Victoria (2006) [https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofha0000sher/page/242 ''Encyclopedia of hair: a cultural history''], Greenwood Publishing Group. p. 242. {{ISBN|0313331456}}</ref>\n\n====Japan====\n[[File:TANASHI CIMG5169.jpg|thumb|Japanese woman with long hair]]\nIn the medieval Japan, [[Heian period|heian]] men were not very interested in a woman's physical beauty and rarely had an opportunity to see it. The only physical attribute of interest was a woman's hair, which had to be thick and longer than she was tall. The fascination with long hair was one reason why a woman's becoming a nun was regarded with such seriousness&nbsp;\u2014 it could never again grow to its full length. This explains why [[Hikaru Genji|Genji]] refuses to let [[Murasaki]] (his de facto wife in the classical Japanese novel ''[[The Tale of Genji]]'') take the tonsure when she is ill.<ref>[[The Tale of Genji]], a novel about courtly life in medieval Japan.</ref>\n\n==In religion==\n\n===Judaism===\n[[File:Flickr_-_Government_Press_Office_(GPO)_-_A_Yemenite_Habani_family_celebrating_Passover.jpg|thumb|[[Habbani Jews]] feasting in a [[Passover]] [[Seder]]. Habbani Jews tend to lengthen their hair.]]\nIn the [[Old Testament]], the [[Nazirites]] would go for long periods of time without cutting their hair to show devotion to God.<ref>{{Bibleverse||Numbers|6:5}}, {{Bibleverse||Numbers|6:18\u201319}}</ref> [[Samson]] is one example; his strength depended upon his refraining from cutting his hair, described as worn in \"seven locks\".<ref name = judge>{{Bibleverse||Judges|13\u201316}}</ref>\n\nStrict Orthodox [[Judaism]] forbids men from cutting their [[Payot|sidelocks]], but other hair may be kept as desired. Hair is not cut during a time of mourning. The Torah in Deuteronomy 14:1 prohibits removing hair in mourning for the dead.\n\n===Christianity===\nIn the [[New Testament]], [[Saint Paul]] (formerly Saul of Tarsus) wrote, \"Doth not even nature itself teach you, that, if a man have long hair, it is a shame unto him? But if a woman have long hair, it is a glory to her: for her hair is given her for a covering. But if any seem contentious, we have no such custom, neither do the churches of God.\"<ref name = kjv>KJV {{Bibleverse|1|Corinthians|11:14\u201316|KJV}}</ref>\n\n===Islam===\n[[File:Rebabah.jpg|thumb|[[Transjordanian]] [[Bedouin]] with shoulder length hair, during [[World War II]]]]\nIn the Muslim world, it seems the trend of hair styles is now favouring short over long in men. In the past, Bedouin Muslims often wore their hair in long braids, but influences from the Western world have caused a change in attitudes. Bedouins are now less likely to have long hair.<ref>{{Citation |last=Massad |first=Joseph |title=Colonial Effects |location=New York |publisher=Columbia University Press |year=2001 |isbn=0-231-12322-1 |pages=137\u2013140, 208\u2013210}}</ref> Islamic countries in [[North Africa]] such as [[Egypt]] view long hair in men as modernist and in one case the Egyptian police viewed it as Satanic and a sign of an infidel.<ref>{{Citation |last=Heper |first=Metin |title=Ismet Inonu: the Making of a Turkish Statesman |location=Boston |publisher=Brill Academic Publishers |year=1998 |page=153 |isbn=90-04-09919-0}}</ref> Spanish rulers during the [[Medieval Period]] suspected long-haired males to be Moors or Moriscos, therefore long hair was forbidden since it was believed to be a Moorish custom. However, modern North African men have adopted Western short hair.\n\nMuslims regard the [[Prophet Muhammad]] as the best example to live by, and try to emulate him whenever possible. The Islamic [[Prophet Muhammad]] reportedly in [[Sahih Muslim]] had hair that \"hung over his shoulders and earlobes\".<ref>[[Sahih Muslim]] Book 30 Number 5773: \"Qatada reported: I asked Anas b. Malik: How was the hair of Allah's Messenger? Thereupon he said: His hair was neither very curly nor very straight, and they hung over his shoulders and earlobes.\"</ref> [[Sahih Bukhari]], regarded the most authentic of [[hadith]], also supports this using a prime example of the prophet [[Jesus in Islam|Isa]] (Jesus).<ref>[[Sahih Al-Bukhari]] Volume 7 Book 72 Number 788: \"Narrated Al-Bara':\nI did not see anybody in a red cloak looking more handsome than the Prophet Narrated Malik: The hair of the Prophet used to hang near his shoulders. Narrated Shu'ba: The hair of the Prophet used to hang down to the earlobes.\"</ref> The Prophet Muhammad has also described Jesus as \"having long hair reaching his ear lobes.\"<ref>Sahih Al-Bukhari Volume 9 Book 87 Number 128 : Narrated 'Abdullah bin 'Umar: Allah's Apostle said, \"I saw myself (in a dream) near the Ka'ba last night, and I saw a man with whitish red complexion, the best you may see amongst men of that complexion having long hair reaching his earlobes which was the best hair of its sort, and he had combed his hair and water was dropping from it, and he was performing the Tawaf around the Ka'ba while he was leaning on two men or on the shoulders of two men. I asked, 'Who is this man?' Somebody replied, '(He is) Messiah, son of Mary.' Then I saw another man with very curly hair, blind in the right eye which looked like a protruding out grape. I asked, 'Who is this?' Somebody replied, '(He is) Messiah, Ad-Dajjal.'\"</ref> Malik's Muwatta 51.2.6 reported, Yahya related to me from Malik from Yahya ibn Said that Abu Qatada al-Ansari said to the Messenger of Allah, may Allah bless him and grant him peace, \"I have a lot of hair which comes down to my shoulders, shall I comb it?'' The Messenger of Allah, may Allah bless him and grant him peace, said, \"Yes, and honour it.\" Sometimes Abu Qatada oiled it twice in one day because the Messenger of Allah, may Allah bless him and grant him peace, said to him. \"Honour it.\"\n\nWith regards to women, neither Qur'an nor Sunnah explicitly state that women cannot cut their hair. Hadith does mention that women should not imitate men, and vice versa, and hence many scholars on this assumption, decree that women should let their hair grow longer than the hair of the Prophet, reaching beyond their shoulders, as hadith mentions that the Prophet had his hair between his shoulder and his earlobes. (He described Jesus's hair, which hung to his earlobes, as long.<ref>Sahih Al-Bukhari Volume 9 Book 87 Number 128</ref>)\n\nHowever, according to some hadiths regarding the rules of [[awrah]], women are required to grow hair long, long enough that it would cover the breasts or as much awrah parts of the body when they're being buried, because she lacks clothes and long hair would be used as a covering instead.\n\nSome Muslims are also opposed to men having long hair as it is also important in Islam to have clear differences (in appearance) between sexes. And generally these cultures encourage women to have long hair and men to have short hair.<ref name = islam>{{Citation |last1=Joseph |first1=Suad |first2=Afsaneh |last2=Najmabadi |authorlink2=Afsaneh Najmabadi |title=Encyclopedia of Women & Islamic Cultures: Family, Body, Sexuality and Health, Volume 3 |location=Boston |publisher=Brill Academic Publishers |year=2005 |page=35 |isbn=90-04-12819-0}}</ref> The [[Taliban]] in Afghanistan viewed long hair for men as a western influence, and punished it by arrest and forced haircuts,<ref name = taliban>{{Citation |last=Rashid |first=Ahmed |title=Taliban: Islam, oil and the new great game in central Asia |publisher=I B Tauris & Co Ltd |year=2002 |page=219 |isbn=1-86064-830-4}}</ref> although this would be a direct contradiction of the [[sunnah]] of the Prophet. Similar measures have been taken by Islamists in [[Iraq]].<ref>{{Citation |first=Sudarsan |last=Raghavan |journal=The Washington Post |date=2006-10-06 |url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/15149242/ |title=Another freedom cut short: Iraq's barbers under threat |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080725055030/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/15149242/ |archivedate=2008-07-25 |access-date=2009-05-19 }}</ref> In spite of this, several Taliban affiliated members of the [[Mehsud]] clan are recognisable by their long hair.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/3745962.stm |title=South Asia &#124; Profile: Abdullah Mehsud |publisher=BBC News |date=2007-07-24 |accessdate=2013-10-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/pakistan/7672214/Taliban-leader-Hakimullah-Mehsud-threatens-US-months-after-death.html |title=Taliban leader Hakimullah Mehsud threatens US months after 'death' |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=2010-05-03 |accessdate=2013-10-27}}</ref> The [[Saudi people|Saudi]] Islamist fighter [[Amir Khattab]] was also notable for his long hair. [[Dervishes]] of some [[Sufi]] orders, such as the [[Kasnazani]], often have long hair and whirl it around during rituals.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/21/world/africa/21iht-sufis.html | work=The New York Times | first=Edward | last=Wong | title=Iraq's Sufis attacked as strife widens | date=2005-08-22}}</ref>\n\n===Sikhism===\nFor [[Sikhs]], [[Kesh (Sikhism)|Kesh]] is the practice of allowing one's hair to grow naturally as a symbol of devotion to God and lack of worldliness.<ref name = fowler>{{cite book |last=Fowler |first=Jeaneane |title=World Religions: an Introduction for Students |location=Brighton |publisher=Sussex Academic Press |year=1997 |page=[https://archive.org/details/worldreligionsin0000unse/page/352 352] |isbn=1-898723-48-6 |url=https://archive.org/details/worldreligionsin0000unse/page/352 }}</ref>\n{{Unreferenced section|date=August 2014}}\n\nThe Sikhs were commanded by Guru Gobind Singh at the Baisakhi Amrit Sanchar in 1699 to wear long uncut hair called [[Kesh (Sikhism)|Kesh]] at all times to signify the strength and vitality of the Sikh people. This was one of the 'five requisites of faith', collectively called Kakars that form the external visible identifiers to clearly affirm a Sikh's commitment and dedication to the order (Hukam) of the tenth master and made one a member of the Khalsa. The Khalsa is the \"Saint-Soldier\" of Guru Gobind Singh who stated the following:\n\"He does not recognize anyone else except One Lord, not even the bestowal of charities, performance of merciful acts, austerities and restraint on pilgrim-stations; the perfect light of the Lord illuminates his heart, then consider him as the immaculate Khalsa.\" (Guru Gobind Singh in the Dasam Granth page 1350)\n\nThe Kesh or unshorn long hair is an indispensable part of the human body as created by waheguru that is the mainstay of the 'Jivan Jaach' and the Rehni that was prescribed by Guru Gobind Singh Sahib by which a Sikh is clearly and quickly identified, Kesh. The kanga, another requisite of faith is usually tucked behind the \"Rishi Knot\" and tied under the turban. The uncut long head hair and the beard in the case of men forms the main kakar for the Sikhs.\n\nKESADHARI, a term defining a Sikh as one who carries on his head the full growth of his kes (hair) which he never trims or cuts for any reason. Anyone, Sikh or non-Sikh, may keep the hair unshorn, but for the Sikh kes, unshorn hair, is a requisite of faith and an inviolable vow. The Sikh Rahit Maryada published by the Shiromani Gurdwara Prabandhak Committee, statutory body for the control and management of Sikh shrines and by extension for laying down rules about Sikh beliefs and practices, issued in 1945, after long and minute deliberations among Sikh scholars and theologians, defines a Sikh thus:\nEvery Sikh who has been admitted to the rites of amrit, i.e. who has been initiated as a Sikh, must allow his hair to grow to its full length. This also applies to those born of Sikh families but [who] have not yet received the rites of amrit of the tenth master, Guru Gobind Singh.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Personal grooming|Grooming]]\n*[[Haircut]]\n*[[Hair extensions]]\n*[[Hair stick]]\n*[[Lady Godiva]]\n*[[Long hair fetishism]], a form of ''Trichophilia''\n*[[Rapunzel]]\n\n==Images==\n*[[commons:Category:Female long hair in art|Female long hair in art]] (Gallery at Wikimedia commons)\n*[[commons:Category:Female long hair|Female long hair photos]] (Gallery at Wikimedia commons)\n*[[commons:Category:Male long hair in art|Male long hair in art]] (Gallery at Wikimedia commons)\n*[[commons:Category:Male long hair|Male long hair photos]] (Gallery at Wikimedia commons)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book |ref=Byrd |last1=Byrd |first1=Ayana |first2=Lori |last2=Tharps |title=Hair Story |location=New York |publisher=St. Martin's Griffin |year=2002 |isbn=0-312-28322-9 |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780312283223 }}\n\n==External links==\n* {{commons category-inline}}\n* {{Wiktionary-inline}}\n\n{{Human hair}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Long Hair}}\n[[Category:Hairstyles]]\n[[Category:Pejorative terms for people]]\n[[Category:Heavy metal fashion]]\n", "name_user": "41.112.147.148", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(I added more information and tips on long hair)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_hair"}
